How to Host a Website using
a Raspberry Pi
Host a website for free right from your house
This tutorial was last updated on 9/24/19.
In this tutorial, we will be hosting a website from a Raspberry Pi. We recommend having
a Raspberry Pi 3B+ or the Pi 4. With these models, networking speeds have been
improved incredibly.
A Raspberry Pi 3B+ can be seen to the right. This model of the
Raspberry Pi supports newer networking standards, like 5 GHz Wi-
Fi networks and 802.11ac. It also has an improved Ethernet port,
handling up to 40 MB/s, which is three times more than the original
Raspberry Pi 3B.
Image copyright to Raspberry Pi Foundation.
Before you get started, you should already have a page created. If you want to learn
HTML, look at our HTML Basics tutorial. You will learn to make a basic page with
headers, paragraphs, and images.
Hosting a website doesnt have to be a pain, or
cost hundreds of dollars per month to host it. If
you are making a site to handle thousands of
visitors, or just a few, you can do it with a
Raspberry Pi.
Also, you should check if your Internet Service Provider (ISP provides your internet.
Some examples are CenturyLink and Spectrum) allows hosting websites from your
network. We found this out the hard way, and CenturyLink shut down the computers
internet connection until we took the site down. We tried twice because we didnt know
what happened at first. Then we figured out what it was after a few months and made
the move to GitHub.
If you are ready to continue, go ahead and power on your Raspberry Pi. If you havent
set up your Pi yet, you should see this video, from the Raspberry Pi Foundation.
Open Terminal
We will use the Terminal for most of this tutorial. You should get used to using the
terminal, because many commands on a Linux-style system are through its terminal.
First, open the Terminal program, located on the Taskbar.
A box should appear looking like this:
You should see the text, pi@raspberrypi: ~ $. This is where we will enter commands.
pi is the user that is logged in. If you change your username, this will change.
@raspberrypi means that you are working on the computer. This will change if you
decide to rename the computer. And finally, the : ~ $ shows the current directory you
are in and that it is ready for a command. This always starts in the home directory,
which is represented with a tilde.
We will be updating the package list on the Pi so when you install Apache, you get the
latest version. It is a good idea to run this before you install anything.
At the prompt, type sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade. This tells the
computer to temporarily run as root, use the apt package manager, get a package
update list, AND upgrade the packages.
This can take a while if you havent updated in a long time. Typically, newer installs of
Raspbian will automatically update when you first turn it on. When it finishes, keep the
terminal open.
Install Apache
Apache is a program that will host your HTML files. Later, you can customize it to run
PHP, CGI, etc., but that is beyond the scope of this project.
To install Apache, type sudo apt-get install apache2. Once the install is completed,
open a web browser and type in the IP address of the Pi. If you dont know what it is,
you can type ifconfig at the terminal.
The image above shows the result of the ifconfig command. Note that your IP address
will probably be different from the one shown above.
When you navigate to the Pis IP address, you should see something like this:
The page you see is the default Apache page on
Debian devices (Raspbian is a port of Debian). This
page has some important information that you may
want to save for later, especially if you decide to
modify your configuration.
The websites files are usually stored in a location
called /var/www/html. If you navigate to this, one file
will be present: index.html.
From the terminal, you can type cd /var/www/html to change the current directory to
Apaches page directory. If you type dir, a list of files will appear. Right now, there is
only one file. That file is the one you saw when you went to the Pis IP address.
When you have an HTML file for the first page of your website, make sure it is named
index.html, and put it in /var/www/html, making sure you replaced Apaches default
page. Try navigating to the Pis IP address again, and you should see your page!
